🎯 How to Read This Analysis

Correlation Matrix: High correlations (>0.7) suggest stocks move together, limiting diversification benefits.

Mean Return: Average return over 250-day periods. Higher is generally better, but consider volatility.

Success Rate: Percentage of periods with positive returns. Higher rates suggest more consistent performance.

Volatility: Measure of price fluctuation. Higher volatility means more risk but potentially higher returns.

Sharpe Ratio: Risk-adjusted return measure. Higher values indicate better risk-adjusted performance.
